<subsection xml:id="subsec-Angles-on-a-tranversal">
    <title>Angles on a transversal</title>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            A <term>transversal</term> is any line that intersects two straight lines at distinct points.
        </p>

        <p>
            When a transversal cuts two parallel lines, several angles are formed by these two intersections.
                Those are called transversal angles. Those types of angles on a transversal are given below:
        </p>

        <p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Corresponding angles
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Co-interior Angles
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Alternate interior angles 
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                    <p>
                        Alternate Exterior angles
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Corresponding-angles">
        <title>Corresponding angles</title>

        <definition xml:id="def-corresponding-angles">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Corresponding angles are the angles which are formed in matching corners or corresponding corners 
                    with the transversal when two parallel lines are intersected by any other line (i.e. the transversal). 
                </p>

                    <p>
                    Here ia an activity for you to explore on corresponding angles
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Corresponding angles(Created with GeoGebraÂ®,[Geogebra Content Team])</caption>
                    <interactive xml:id="geogebra-Corresponding-angles" platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="4:3">
                    <slate xml:id="geogebra-corresponding-angles" surface="geogebra" material="rcj8bsfm" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                    </slate>
                    </interactive>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find the value of angle <m>k</m> in the figure below.
            </p>
        
            <image>
                <shortdescription>Corresponding angles</shortdescription>
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw[fill=green] (0,0) -- (60:.35cm) arc (60:180:.35cm);
                        \draw(120:0.5cm) node {$k$};
                        \draw[fill=white] (0,0) -- (right:.45cm) arc (0:60:.45cm);
                        \draw[fill=white] (0,0) -- (180:.5cm) arc (180:240:.5cm);
                        \draw[fill=white] (0,0) -- (240:.4cm) arc (240:360:.4cm); 

                        \begin{scope}[shift={(60:2cm)}]
                        \draw[fill=white] (0,0) -- (180:.4cm) arc (180:240:.4cm);
                        \draw[fill=white] (0,0) -- (240:.3cm) arc (240:360:.3cm);
                        \draw[white] (0,0) -- (360:.45cm) arc (360:420:.45cm);
                        \draw[fill=yellow] (0,0) -- (60:.3cm) arc (60:180:.3cm);
                        \draw(120:0.5cm) node {$110^\circ$};
                        \end{scope}

                        \begin{scope}[thick]
                        \draw  (60:-1cm) -- (60:3cm);
                        \draw[red]                   (-2,0) -- (3,0);
                        \draw[blue,shift={(60:2cm)}] (-3,0) -- (2,0);
                        \end{scope}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
   
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Corresponding angles are equal.
            </p>
            <p>
                Angle <m>k</m> corresponds with <m>110^\circ.</m> 
            </p>
            <p>
                Angle <m>k = 110^\circ.</m> 
            </p>
        </solution>
        </example>
    
    </subsubsection>
   
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Co-interior-angle">
                <title>Co-interior angle</title>
                <activity>
                    <p>
                        Work in groups
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>1.</m> Draw a pair of parallel lines and a transversal
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>2. </m> Mark the angles as shown below.
                    </p>

                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>Co-interior angles</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw[fill=red] (0,0) -- (60:.3cm) arc (60:180:.3cm);
                                \draw(120:0.4cm) node {$o$};

                                \draw[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (right:.4cm) arc (0:60:.4cm);
                                \draw(30:0.6cm) node {$p$};

                                \draw[fill=yellow] (0,0) -- (180:.5cm) arc (180:240:.5cm);

                                \draw[fill=green] (0,0) -- (240:.35cm) arc (240:360:.35cm);

                                

                                \begin{scope}[shift={(60:2cm)}]
                                \draw[fill=yellow] (0,0) -- (180:.4cm) arc (180:240:.4cm);
                                \draw (30:-0.6cm) node {$m$};

                                \draw[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (240:.35cm) arc (240:360:.35cm);
                                \draw (-60:0.6cm) node {$n$};

                                \draw[fill=green] (0,0) -- (60:.35cm) arc (60:180:.35cm);

                                \draw[fill=red] (0,0) -- (right:.4cm) arc (0:60:.4cm);
                                
                                \end{scope}

                                \begin{scope}[thick]
                                \draw (60:-1cm)  -- (60:3cm);
                                \draw[black]                   (-2,0) -- (3,0);
                                \draw[black,shift={(60:2cm)}] (-3,0) -- (2,0);
        

                                \end{scope}
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    
                    <p>
                        <m>3. </m> Cut the angles <m>n</m> and <m>p</m> using a pair of scissors
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>4.</m> Place the angles on a straight line.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        What do you notice?
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>5</m> Share your findings with other learners in class.
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <em>Learning point</em>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        Angles <m>n</m> and <m>p</m> are co-interior. Co-interior angles add upto <m>180^\circ</m>.
                    </p>

                </activity>

                <example>
                    <statement>

                    <p>
                        What is the value of angle <m>n</m> in the figure below?
                    </p>

                    <image>
                        <shortdescription>Co-interior angles</shortdescription>
                        <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw[fill=red] (0,0) -- (60:.3cm) arc (60:180:.3cm);
                                \draw[fill=red] (0,0) -- (right:.4cm) arc (0:60:.4cm);
                                \draw(30:0.8cm) node {$50^\circ$};
                                \draw[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (180:.5cm) arc (180:240:.5cm);
                                \draw[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (240:.35cm) arc (240:360:.35cm);

                                \begin{scope}[shift={(60:2cm)}]
                                \draw[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (180:.4cm) arc (180:240:.4cm);
                                \draw[fill=blue] (0,0) -- (240:.35cm) arc (240:360:.35cm);
                                \draw (-60:0.5cm) node {$n$};
                                \draw[fill=red] (0,0) -- (60:.35cm) arc (60:180:.35cm);
                                \draw[fill=red] (0,0) -- (right:.4cm) arc (0:60:.4cm);
                                \end{scope}

                                \begin{scope}[thick]
                                \draw (60:-1cm)  -- (60:3cm);
                                \draw[black]                   (-2,0) -- (3,0);
                                \draw[black,shift={(60:2cm)}] (-3,0) -- (2,0);
                                \end{scope}        
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                    </statement>

                    <solution>
                    <p>
                        Co-interior angles add up to <m>180^\circ</m>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            n + 50^\circ = 180^\circ
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            n + 50^\circ - 50^\circ = 180^\circ - 50^\circ
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <me>
                            n = 130^\circ
                        </me>
                        
                    </p>
                    </solution>

                </example>

        </subsubsection>

        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-Alternate-interior-and-alternate-exterior-angles">
            <title>Alternate interior and alternate exterior angles</title>
            <p>
                    
                Alternate angles in parallel lines are angles that occur on opposite sides of the transversal line and have the same size.     
            </p>

            <!-- <figure>
                    <caption>Alternate angles</caption>
                    <interactive xml:id="geogebra-Alternate-angles-example" platform="geogebra" width="90%" aspect="4:3">
                    <slate xml:id="geogebra-alternate-angles-example" surface="geogebra" material="xxrpmwrj" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                    </slate>
                    </interactive>
            </figure> -->

            <activity>
                <p>
                    Here is an exercise for you to explore on alternate angles  
                </p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Alternate angles</caption>
                    <interactive xml:id="geogebra-Alternate-angles" platform="geogebra" width="100%" aspect="4:3">
                    <slate xml:id="geogebra-alternate-angles" surface="geogebra" material="pc6q83ds" aspect="4:3">
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                    </slate>
                    </interactive>
                </figure>
                <p>
                From the given figure, we have the following categories of alternate angles.
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Alternate interior angles</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle u \text{ and } \angle v</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle r  \text{ and } \angle h</m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Alternate exterior angles</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle p \text{ and } \angle t</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>

                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\angle q \text{ and } \angle s</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>

            <p>
                Alternate angles are also called the <term>Z</term> angles and can be identified by
                drawing a <term>Z</term> on the figure as shown in the figure above.
            </p>

            </activity>
    
        </subsubsection>

    </subsection>